STRINGTABLE DISCARDABLE
BEGIN
    832 "Authorize Sortie Criteria"
    833 "Sorties per Period"
    834 "-"
    835 "On the morning of 25  June 1950, North Korean troops spearheaded by T-34 tanks swept south of the 38th parallel. Unprepared, ROK Forces were driven back. In the month that followed, US aircraft pounded advancing communist columns. These aerial strikes were so punishing that the North Koreans were compelled to restrict their movements to the hours of darkness.\nIn the Air, American Jets outclassed the North Korean Airforce and effectively removed it as a threat to the allied ground forces.\nTroops were hastily committed to the effort. Elements of the 24th US Infantry Division were moved into place, south of Seoul, to blunt an enemy thrust down the western corridor. Outnumbered 10 to 1, the Americans could only hope to fight a delaying action until reinforcements arrived.\n"
    836 "By the beginning of August, UN Forces were contracting to form a perimeter around the port of Pusan where vital supplies and reinforcements were landed continuously. The attacking North Koreans grew weaker as their over-stretched supply lines were increasingly compromised by interdiction sorties.\nSensing that the last chance for victory was slipping away, the North Koreans launched many bloody and desperate assaults along the perimeter. Although some gains were made, superior UN firepower stopped the Communists from making a significant breakthrough.\nUnlike their adversaries, UN troops could call on aircraft for assistance. The F51 Mustang, capable of operating from dirt strips, flew constant sorties along the front in support of UN troops.\n"
    837 "On September 18, following the marine landing at Inchon, the 8th Army commenced its breakout from the Pusan pocket. Faced with capture or destruction, the communist forces had no option but to flee northwards in disarray. Snapping at their heels, UN troops rapidly closed the net across the south of the country.\nOn September 27, UN Forces crossed the 38th parallel with orders to achieve the total destruction of the North Korean army. From the air, UN aircraft inflicted telling blows on the retreating enemy.\n"
    838 "During November, UN Forces engaged in combat with infiltrating Chinese forces as they advanced to the Yalu River. UN aircraft tasked with cutting links to China came under increasing pressure from Chinese MiG 15s. The F80 was outclassed. The USAF responded to this threat by dispatching a wing each of F86A Sabres and F84E Thunderjets to Korea.\nOn November 20, the Chinese launched a massive offensive that sent UN forces reeling southwards. Large numbers of UN troops, cut-off by the rapid enemy advance, escaped to the eastern ports under cover of airforce fire.\nBridges and supply routes were hammered by UN bombers to stem the flow of Chinese Forces. The Sabres and Thunderjets flew CAP and escort missions along the Yalu to protect the vulnerable bombers.\n"
    839 "The UN continued its withdrawal throughout the early days of '51 to successive lines below the 38th parallel. An attempt to hold Seoul failed and UN troops were evacuated from the docks at Inchon. The situation was a complete reversal of events from the previous year.\nThe Chinese advance began to stall. Their over-stretched supply lines could not cope with demands from the front. The UN eventually stabilized a new front between Pyongtaek and Wonju from which they were able to launch new operations aimed at regaining the initiative.\nCommunist Forces recoiled and waited for a new and bigger supply base to form in the forward areas. With the supplies in place they would be able to launch their Spring Offensive.\n"
    840 "Inflict heavy casualties on the advancing enemy columns. The enemy push must be slowed or the 24th Division's blocking positions will be overrun."
    841 "Fly ground attack missions against NKA Forces attacking in the Taegu sector. The perimeter must hold. An enemy breakthrough will fold the allied defense."
    842 "You must destroy supply dumps and bridges that feed supplies to the rapidly crumbling North Korean Army. Any NKA forces that fight their way out of the UN net will rally in the north."
    843 "Ensure that your bombers can operate safely in the skies of North Korea by flying close escort missions and barrier patrols along the Yalu. The bombers must hit targets that will slow the flow of Chinese men and materials into the Northwest. "
    844 "The UN must hold out until the end of Spring, at which point the Reds will abandon their offensive and agree to talk peace. During this period, you must prevent supplies from reaching front-line positions by hitting supply dumps and bridges, and also assist friendly ground forces directly by flying close air support missions.\nThe war is lost if UN Forces are pushed from their starting positions at Pyongtaek and Wonju. If the UN takes the North's Capital, Pyongyang, then the war is concluded with a UN victory.\n"
    845 "Selection Results"
    846 "Directive"
    847 "Fighters"
END
