STRINGTABLE DISCARDABLE
BEGIN
    768 "MiGs destroyed"
    769 "U.N. aircraft lost"
    770 "Last Msn. Kills "
    771 "Vehicles reported"
    772 "Vehicles destroyed"
    773 "Armor units destroyed"
    774 "Artillery pieces destroyed"
    775 "Platoons neutralized"
    776 "Last Mission"
    777 "Type"
    778 "Telling blows from UN air strikes have compelled the NKPA to restrict its movements to the hours of darkness. Along with the delaying action fought by the 24th Division, enough time has been bought for reinforcements landing at Pusan to be deployed along the Naktong River."
    779 "Aided by excellent air support, UN troops have held back repeated attacks from superior numbers of NKPA troops. This has bought enough time for MacArthur to launch his bold counter-stroke: an amphibious landing at Inchon that will open up a second front far behind Communist Lines."
    780 "UN air power has inflicted serious damage along the enemy's lines of retreat. Large numbers of NKPA troops have been captured or destroyed. UN and ROK troops have encountered light resistance as they envelop the North's Capital, Pyongyang."
    781 "The Chinese attempt to cut off the 8th army has failed. Although some heavy equipment was abandoned, most troop units managed to escape intact. X Corps was successfully evacuated from the port of Hungnam along with its gear and 80,000 refugees. Our bombers and fighters have played a key role in holding up the enemy advance."
    782 "-"
    783 "UN air power failed to stem the North Korean advance and as a result the 24th Division was rolled up. NKPA forces moved rapidly on the port of Pusan before UN reinforcements could be deployed, leaving UN commanders little choice but to order a mass evacuation. The whole of Korea is now in Communist hands."
END
STRINGTABLE DISCARDABLE
BEGIN
    784 "NKPA forces have broken through the perimeter and the entire front has folded. UN forces are pulling back to Pusan where a mass evacuation is underway. Korea will be abandoned to the Communist aggressors."
    785 "The UN failed to capitalize on the NKPA's retreat. Enough of the Red Army escaped northwards to constitute a serious and continued threat."
    786 "MiG Alley has proved a no-go area for allied bombers. Even America's premier fighter was not equal to the task of protecting the bombers from Chinese MiG 15s. As a result, vast numbers of Chinese troops have swept across the north of Korea to trap whole UN Divisions."
    787 "-"
    788 "Data Rate"
    789 "Software Driver"
    790 "Head Up MigDisplay"
    791 "Control SFX Volume"
    792 "Ambient SFX Volume"
    793 "UN Forces have captured Pyongyang and Chinese forces are retreating northwards. Delegations have arrived at Panmunjom to discuss peace. It is believed that the high cost of sustaining the war and continued pressure from UN Forces will cause the Chinese to abandon North Korea."
    794 "Delegations have finally gathered around the peace-table at Panmunjom to talk terms. The UN is in a favorable position. The front has been pushed north of the 38th parallel and the Communist delegation seems eager to conclude talks quickly in order to freeze the front before any more of the North is lost to them."
    795 "Delegations have finally gathered around the peace-table at Panmunjom to talk terms. The UN is in a favorable position. The front has been pushed north of the 38th parallel and the Communist delegation seems eager to conclude talks quickly in order to freeze the front before any more of the North is lost to them."
    796 "Peace-talks have been initiated. Delegates have arrived at Panmunjom to talk terms. The Communists have built deep bunkers and interlocking positions along a line near to the 38th parallel. Fighting will continue in this area for another two years while the delegates at the Peace Table argue over terms."
    797 "Peace-talks have been initiated. Delegates have arrived at Panmunjom to talk terms. The Communists have built deep bunkers and interlocking positions along a line near to the 38th parallel. Fighting will continue in this area for another 2 years while the delegates at the Peace Table argue over terms."
    798 "Delegations from both sides have arrived at Panmunjom to discuss peace. The front line is situated below the 38th parallel and this puts the UN in a poor position. Talks are proving difficult, with the Communist delegation believing it is in a position to dictate terms and ROK president Syngman Rhee demanding that the talks be abandoned in favor of continued military action."
    799 "Morale is at an all-time low. This is the third time that the UN alliance has been driven back into the tip of the peninsula. Commanders agree that unless drastic action is taken, by increasing ground strength and expanding the air campaign into Mainland China, the South will ultimately be lost. The War is escalating..."
END
STRINGTABLE DISCARDABLE
BEGIN
    1952 "%i %s out of %s were encountered by another air group over %s."
    1953
                            "We missed out on some action. Another group attacked %i %s out of %s near %s."
    1954 "We saw a squadron of about %i %s from %s over %s. It was not engaged."
    1955 "A hostile squadron of %i %s from %s was encountered by our group near %s. We did not engage."
    1956 "A dogfight involving over %i %s was spotted near %s. We left them to it."
    1957 "Spottted %i %s from %s near %s. We got close enough to make an I.D but not close enough for combat."
    1958 "Identified and attacked a group of %i %s operating out of %s. Hope we have more luck next time we patrol near %s."
    1959 "We mixed it up with a group of %i %s from %s while patrolling near %s. We definitely landed some hits!"
    1960 "Engaged a group of %i %s from %s and definitely bagged some kills. Our designated patrol region was %s."
    1961 "Our flight of %i %s took off from %s."
    1962 "Bent a wing on my %s. Any landing you walk away from..."
    1963 "I often watched my buddy writing in this log. Now he is gone I feel I should add my own words about how he met his end..."
    1964 "Had to bring my %s down before reaching %s. Is it too far to walk from %s?"
    1965 "The %s was too damaged to fly back to %s. I put it down at %s and was lucky to walk away from the wreckage."
    1966 "I had to bring my %s down before getting to %s. No real problems with the landing, much to the relief of the ground teams at %s."
    1967 "Returned to base. Mission completed."
END
STRINGTABLE DISCARDABLE
BEGIN
    1968 "A mid-air collision finished today's flying."
    1969 "Got some good hits on the target. Not enough to take it out without another pass."
    1970 "Raked %i vehicles near %s. Didn't see any explosions, though."
    1971 "I can report that the Primary Target was successfully destroyed."
    1972 "Engaged a %i strong convoy near %s. We went in hard and got a number of hits on target."
    1973 "Really lucky to parachute out of the mess."
END
